[1] USA (Ohio)
Date: Fri 23 Dec 2022
Source: Infectious Disease Special Edition [edited]
https://www.idse.net/Immunology-Vaccination/Article/12-22/Measles-Ohio-Outbreak/69051


The politicization of vaccines during the COVID-19 pandemic may be increasing vaccine hesitancy for other vaccinations once considered routine, particularly inoculations for preventable childhood diseases. This hesitancy has exacerbated a measles outbreak in central Ohio, health officials said.

Mysheika Roberts, the health commissioner of Columbus, Ohio, said during a media briefing by the Big Cities Health Coalition (BCHC) that of the approximately 106 cases of measles in the United States in 2022, "as of this morning (20 Dec [2022]) we have 81 confirmed cases here in central Ohio."

Dr Roberts, the board chair of BCHC, which comprises the public health officials in 35 of the nation's largest metropolitan areas, serving a population of 61 million -- or one in 5 Americans -- said, "Coming off the heels of this worldwide pandemic, communities are now facing a tripledemic of disease. Health systems all across the country are being overrun with cases of RSV [respiratory syncytial virus], COVID-19, and now the flu.

"We are also faced with a 'new,' and yes, preventable, disease outbreak, and that disease is measles," she added. She said central Ohio is experiencing the largest outbreak of measles in the United States since 2019.

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) said the 106 cases of measles are occurring in 5 jurisdictions (https://www.cdc.gov/measles/cases-outbreaks.html). Of the 81 cases in central Ohio, 29 patients have been hospitalized, according to Dr Roberts. Reasons for the hospitalizations range from dehydration to pneumonia, as well as neurologic conditions with some patients requiring intensive care.

CDC estimates that hospitalization rates for measles are usually 20% to 25%, but "our hospitalization rate is much higher". Dr Roberts attributed the rate to the cases' young ages. With measles, young children can easily become dehydrated, she said, and are more likely to require hospitalization.

"Seventy-six of these 81 cases are unvaccinated, most by choice, while 22 cases are under the age of 12 months, so they're too young to be vaccinated. The remaining cases are old enough to have at least one MMR [measles-mumps-rubella] vaccine; 23 cases are old enough for 2 of the MMR vaccines as recommended," Dr Roberts said. Of the 81 cases, 76 are 5 years old and under, she said.

"Our investigation, thus far, has shown that parents chose not to have their children vaccinated due to a persistent and incorrect belief that the MMR vaccine causes autism," Dr. Roberts said. "While we continue to address this outbreak and the causes of it, we know that it is indicative of what's to come if current vaccine attitudes persist in the United States."

"Over the winter holidays, the nation's public health officials, such as our BCHC members, are working to marshal still-scarce resources to fight these emerging and ongoing health threats," said Chrissie Juliano, the BCHC executive director. "At the same time, they're confronting a public that is increasingly skeptical of vaccines. Vaccines are one of the most effective tools we have to save lives and avoid severe disease."

Ms Juliano cited a poll released 16 Dec [2022] by the Kaiser Family Foundation (https://www.kff.org/coronavirus-covid-19/press-release/more-than-4-in-10-republicans-and-a-third-of-parents-now-oppose-schools-requiring-children-to-get-vaccinated-for-measles-and-other-illness-up-since-the-covid-19-pandemic-began/) that found that "overall, nearly 3 in 10 adults (28%) nationally now say that parents should be able to decide not to vaccinate their children for measles, mumps, and rubella rather than those vaccinations being required to attend public schools, up from 16% in a 2019 Pew Research Center poll conducted before the COVID-19 pandemic."

Opposition to childhood vaccination among parents is about 35%, up from 23% in 2019, according to Ms Juliano. "This is an increase since the beginning of the COVID pandemic," Ms Juliano said. "I want to stress that this skepticism is about routine vaccination requirements that have been in place for years and are not specific to COVID. Data show that these attitudes are starting to affect behavior. More children are missing their MMR vaccine since the pandemic began. This trend has real consequences." She called the measles outbreak in Ohio "a dangerous step backwards."

Dr Roberts warned that as vaccines are politicized, "combined with the ongoing and persistent mis- and disinformation on vaccines, which have been nearly impossible to counter even with current data, we are faced with a situation ripe for resurgence of even more vaccine-preventable diseases, much more so than just what we're seeing with measles. Our fear is that if we see more vaccine reluctance or hesitancy moving forward, we are going to see a resurgence of other diseases like hepatitis A or hepatitis B" as well as other preventable diseases like mumps, rubella, and pertussis.

Dr Roberts also noted that while public health officials can isolate confirmed cases of measles, the Ohio state legislature now prohibits quarantining people who were exposed to measles but do not have a confirmed case, even though they have a 90% chance of contracting measles. "That's a perfect example of how we're going backward, and we're not able to use our public health authority for the good of the community," she said. "They can continue to go about their daily lives, go to parties, go to malls, go to the grocery store and expose other people to measles, particularly those who are unvaccinated."

She noted that "these challenges and resulting outbreaks are being met by beleaguered local public health departments like mine, which face chronic underfunding, staff that has burned out from the last several years, and growing mistrust from the public hampering our efforts to protect the health and safety of our communities that we serve." Although there are no quick and easy answers, Dr Roberts said her department is committed to making sure "our communities do not undo all the progress we've made with vaccine-preventable diseases over the last several decades. We are at a very critical point," and this outbreak, as well as the tripledemic, further "illustrates why our work is so important and so crucial."

[byline: Tom Rosenthal]

