[3] India (Mumbai)
Date: Sun 25 Dec 2022
Source: Mint [edited]
https://www.livemint.com/news/india/measles-mumbai-cases-rise-to-514-tally-in-maharashtra-at-1162-11671931515062.html


Mumbai has reported 2 new cases of measles, taking the total infection tally to 514 while the death toll remains unchanged. Meanwhile, measles cases in Maharashtra stood at 1162 on Friday [23 Dec 2022], while the death toll was 20. Of the 335 beds earmarked for the treatment of measles, only 114 were occupied.

A release by the state government says that 77 827 of the 260 739 children in the 9 month to 5 year age group in 78 health posts have received additional doses of the measles-rubella vaccine. Also, of the 5293 children aged 6-9 months in 21 health posts where the number of cases in the sub-9-month group exceeds 10% of lab-confirmed cases, 1940 were given a "zero dose" of MR vaccine.

The state health department has started a special initiative from 15 Dec [2022] to administer additional doses of measles and rubella vaccines to children aged 9 months to 5 years over a 28-day period.

Measles is a highly infectious virus originating in the nose and throat of an infected child or adult, but it is almost entirely preventable through vaccination. However, it requires 95% vaccine coverage to prevent outbreaks among populations. The commonest symptoms of measles include high fever, tiredness, severe cough, red or bloodshot eyes, and a runny nose. It can also cause red rashes on the body, which start at the head and then spread to various other body parts. Currently, there is no cure for measles, and once a person contracts the virus, it is advisable to get plenty of rest, as the body needs time to recover. Usually, a person recovers from the infection within 10-15 days.

